COMMON PARAMETERS
	-userid user/password - The User id and password of the user
		to use to analyze the schemas. For an applications
		database use the APPS schema. For other databases
		use SYSTEM or some other DBA user.
		To avoid passing this sensitive information on the
		command line, set the following environment variables
		to the appropriate userid and password:
		   export ANALYZE_LOGIN=APPS
		   export ANALYZE_PWD=APPS
	FYI both -schemas and -except are ignored when analyzing stale tables
	-schemas - Either set to ALL or NONE. This parameter is used in
		conjunction with the -except clause to only analyze the
		schemas you want (DEFAULT=ALL)
	-except - When -schemas is set to ALL then schemas specified
		in the -except clause will NOT be analyzed. When -schemas
		is set to NONE then the ONLY schemas analyzed will be the
		ones specified in the -except clause. This combination
		allows you to analyze ALL schemas except for A,B.C in
		one command OR only analyze A,B.C schemas.(DEFAULT=NONE)
	-days_old - This says if the statistics for a table is num days
		old (i.e. if LAST_ANALYZED is less than (SYSDATE - num) )
		then it will be reanalyzed. So if it was just analyzed you
		can tell it to not analyze again by setting -days_old to 1.
		We only pay attention to this when days_old is greater than 0.
		(DEFAULT=0)
	-incremental <Y,N or number >
		This parameter is used in conjunction with -days_old. If
		-days_old is 90 and -incremental is set to Y then every day
		we run $(basename $0) we will analyze 1/90 number of tables. If
		$(basename $0) is run 2 times in one day it will NOT analyze
		1/90 of the tables the second time. if a number is used instead 
		of a Y we will divide the -days_old parameter into it rather 
		than 1.  This is usefull for weekly instead of daily runs 
		(ie set it to 7 for weekly executions)
		(DEFAULT if -days_old > 30 then incremental=Y otherwise
			incremental=N)
	-estimate - Statistics are estimated at this percentage. Setting this
		will also be the default value for estimating stale tables
		unless -gather_stale is set to a number. This value is
		ignored for small and large tables when analyzing individual
		tables (i.e. analyze_type=STALEONLY, MONITOR, or TABLES)  
		(DEFAULT=20)
	-small_table - A small table is one that has a relatively small number
		of rows and should have statistics computed (100%) rather than
		analyzed. (DEFAULT=10000)
	-large_table - A large table is one that is relatively large and will
		be only analyzed at 10%. (DEFAULT=100000000)
	-jobs - How many analyzes to run concurrently. We will kick off this
		many jobs at a time. If -tnsaliases is used we run this
		many jobs for each alias. This is useful for RAC clusters
		where we may want to run 10 jobs on each RAC node. 
		DEFAULT=(cpu_count *3)
	-degree - How many parallel threads to run per job.  This is the DEGREE
		parameter on both FND_STATS and DBMS_STATS, which defaults to 
		the minimum value of the following database parameters: 
		cpu_count and parallel_max_servers.  When used in combination 
		with the 'jobs' parameter, you can really overload a multi-CPU 
		server if you specify high values for both 'jobs' and 'degree'.
		For example, specifying 8 'jobs' with a 'degree' of 5 could 
		result in 40 processes gathering statistics simultaneously.  
		The 'degree' parameter was added to allow us to scale back the 
		use of server resources while still allowing parallel execution
		of the gather processes.
		* Note that this does NOT change the degree of parallelism 
		on the tables or indexes!  Defaults to 1.
	-instance - Setting this will override the environment TWO_TASK. This 
		is different than the tnsaliases as it is used to create the initial 
		DB connection. Once connected the -tnsaliases is used to spawn the 
		child processes.
		(DEFAULT=\$TWO_TASK)
	-tnsaliases - If you are running a RAC cluster you can use this to
		split jobs between nodes.  For example if you have a 3 node
		cluster, then on the node from which you run $(basename $0) you
		have to have a tnsalias which will go to each RAC node
		individually. Therefore you might use
			'-tnsaliases SID1,SID2,SID3'
		which would send an equal number of jobs to each of the nodes
		specified. (DEFAULT=<The current oracle SID or TWO_TASK>)
	-gather_stale - Set this to determine whether or not to analyze
		stale tables. If set to 'N' then no stale tables are analyzed.
		When set to 'Y' then stale tables are analyzed at the same
		percentage as was set for the -estimate parameter. This can
		also be set to a number which would then be used to estimate
		statistics for stale tables at a potentially different
		level than is used fSTALEONLYor gathering statistics at the schema level.
		We ignore schema restrictions for gathering stale tables unless
		the -restrict_stale option is specified.
	-restrict_stale -  Set this to Y to restrict the gathering of stale 
		stats to the same schema/except parameters used for the other
		analyzes.  Set to N to ignore restrictions and analyzed based on merit
		(DEFAULT=Y)
	-table_name - Setting this parameter will force the analyze to only
		analyze specific tables. Wildcards like %TABLE% are acceptable
		Using this flag automatically sets -gather_stale=N. This option
		makes no sense when used with analyze_type=STALEONLY or SCHEMAS
		(DEFAULT=%)
	-dbms - We typically assume that we are dealing with an Apps database.
		To use the standard dbms_stats package instead of fnd_stats
		set this flag.
	-indexes - Set this flag to enable the validation and rebuilding of 
		each index on every table that is analyzed.  This would 
		normally be used in conjunction with the -gather_stale option 
		to validate and rebuild the indexes on just the stale tables.
	-stale_pct - The percent change that is needed for a table to be 
		considered "stale" (DEFAULT=5)
	-huge_table - Set this flag to NO to not analyze tables which take on average
		2 hours to analyze. Setting this to ONLY will only analyze huge 
		tables and setting it to YES (the default) will analyze huge 
		tables as part of normal activities. We only look at $HUGE_TABLE_HISTORY
		days of history so if these tables are not re-analyzed within that period
		they will no longer be considered huge. (DEFAULT=YES)
