 1. Increase shared_pool_size. Start increasing it with 20%.
    
    2. Increase the shared_pool_reserved_size parameter; set it to 10%, or higher but max 50% of the
    new shared_pool_size.
    
    3. According to documentation: OPEN_CURSORS specifies the maximum number of open cursors (handles
    to private SQL areas) a session can have at once. You can use this parameter to prevent a session
    from opening an excessive number of cursors. This parameter also constrains the size of the PL/SQL
    cursor cache which PL/SQL uses to avoid having to reparse as statements are reexecuted by a user.
    It is important to set the value of OPEN_CURSORS high enough to prevent your application from
    running out of open cursors. Its default value is 50.
    
    Setting open_cursors to 3000 implies individual connected sessions can open up to 3000 cursors
    each which would allow a huge amount of shared pool to be used by each session.
    You will usually need a bigger shared pool when you have large values for parameters like:
    - open_cursors
    - processes
    - sessions
    If OPEN_CURSORS is set to a high value then internally a session may hold on to more shared pool
    memory than it needs to. This can result in ORA-4031 errors.
    
    ++ Set OPEN_CURSORS to 1000.
    ++ Check the values MAX_UTILIZATION from V$RESOURCE_LIMIT for PROCESSES and SESSIONS. Adjust
    PROCESSES and SESSIONS parameters accordingly with these values.
    
    
    4. Decrease the value of session_cached_cursors (currently set to 3000 which is huge).
    SESSION_CACHED_CURSORS lets you specify the number of session cursors to cache. Its default value
    is 0. The session_cached_cursors increases the space required in the shared pool also.
    
