    Note 222597.1 Accessing HTTP Server Though WebCache On Same Server Causes  Allow/Deny Directives
    To Be Ignored
    Note 263943.1   Client IP Does Note Pass To Mod_Access Through Web Cache
    
    http://www.securityfocus.com/bid/13418/info
    
    From Oracle HTTP Server perspective...
    
    "UseWebCacheIp On" is a recommended directive to be used to allow the correct IP address to be
    used by mod_access (e.g. logging or restricting by IP). It is used when Oracle Web Cache is in
    front of the Oracle HTTP Server. because its not always used with Oracle Web cache, the default
    was to have if "off" (commented out). But, because of a security concern, it was suggested to
    always have it "On". (uncommenting it).
    
    Internal bug 3171428 explains the issue, how the use of "localhost" can be mixed up with Web
    Cache, and therefore anyone coming through WC was allowed, as if they were localhost, if
    mod_access was configured to allow only "localhost". Therefore, its safer to ensure "UseWebCacheIp
    On" is set. The way to tell if it is, is to check the Apache/Apache/logs/access_log, and verify if
    the client IP address is logged, or the  Server IP address 9where webcache is installed) is
    logged. If the logs use the client IP, everything is ok.
    
    In versions where it was defaulted to Off, the Oracle Security patch readmes (Critical Patch
    Update) stated to uncomment the directive. In the newer versions, it should be uncommented by
    default, and acceptable to all standards (functionality and security). Also, if applying the
    latest Critical Patch Update, customers are ensured all known and fixed vulnerabilities are
    covered (and this was from 2005). Third-party reports may or may not be a reliable source to what
    is vulnerable in Oracle products.
    
    This configuration, the use of "UseWebCacheIp On" should only be in the httpd..conf. It seems in
    this SR, it was uncommented, as requested. Therfore, meeting security standards, as well as
    ensuring mod_access is properly using the client IP.
    
    
    
    ACTION PLAN
    ===========
    
    1. The above research shows what "UseWebCacheIp On" is about, and what was requested from Oracle
    HTTP Server expertise, to ensure customer understands the impact of the directive settting.
    
    2. Customer is requesting that "UseWebCacheIp On" be in the httpd.conf. Its unclear what OnDemand
    has done, or what the current connfiguration is. SR needs to go back to OnDemand to confirm
    settings with customer, and can also check the  Apache/Apache/logs/access_log to ensure the client
    IP address is logged, instead of the Server IP address. (just having multiple addresses in the log
    is enough to proove it).
