4.12.1 SHARED POOL DISK READS and EXTRACTING THE PROBLEM SQL STATEMENT

       The following query should reveal the active sessions, that are using 
       the shared pool that have more than 100000 disk reads.  You may have 
       to run this query several times to become familiar with the culprit 
       SQL and other SQL statements that are present, but performing correctly.

BEGIN>
          column sql_statement heading 'sql statement' format a40 wrap
          select substr(b.username,1,15) username,
             a.disk_reads reads,
             a.executions exec,
             a.disk_reads/decode(a.executions, 0,1,a.executions) rds_exec_ratio,
             a.command_type cmd_type,
             a.sql_text sql_statement
          from   v$sqlarea a, dba_users b
          where  a.parsing_user_id = b.user_id
          and    a.disk_reads > 100000
          order by a.disk_reads desc;
END>

       The following query will show you the names of all the objects in
       the shared pool that take more that 10K of memory as well as if they
       are marked kept or not. For SQL statements, if there are multiple
       versions of a query (usually a bug if the count is more than 3), they 
       will also be indicated in parenthesis. Use the following query to 
       check for problems:

BEGIN>
          select sql_text,
                 loaded_versions,
                 version_count,
                 sharable_mem
          from   v$sqlarea
          where  loaded_versions > 3
          and sharable_mem > 10000
          order by sharable_mem;
END>

       Shared Pool Large Anonymous Blocks.  Typically, you want smaller
       anonymous blocks of PL/SQL code as a design and coding  standard.  If 
       you see evidence of large anonymous blocks, consider breaking these down
       into smaller stored procedures.  Consider keeping the block in the shared
       pool if it cannot be broken down.  Use the following query to identify  
       any blocks that may currently be in the shared pool:

BEGIN>
         Select sql_text
         from v$sqlarea
         where command_type = 47
         and length(sql_text) > 750;
END>



