============================================================================== 
Generic Note
------------------------
I think the cause for your issue is that there is a mismatch between the intended settings in sqlnet.ora and listener.ora. 
Listener is terminating connections and during high volume times, it may create an issue - likely this is a cause for the repeated down conditions.



SQLNET.EXPIRE_TIME is to terminate idle sessions, and is specified in minutes. so 10 minutes.
SQLNET.INBOUND_CONNECT_TIMEOUT is to specify inbound connect time, in seconds, it is set to 300 seconds, or 5 minutes. (default is 60 seconds)

http://docs.oracle.com/cd/B28359_01/network.111/b28317/sqlnet.htm#BIIEEGJH

However, in listener.ora:
CONNECT_TIMEOUT_<listener name> is set to 10 --> this is in seconds, and If the listener does not receive the client request in the time specified, then it terminates the connection.

http://docs.oracle.com/cd/B28359_01/network.111/b28317/listener.htm#i503196

The default value for above is 60 seconds. (both inbound_connect parameters)

Recommendations:

Remove the entries in listener.ora:

CONNECT_TIMEOUT_PBAAUI = 10 
And reload the listener.

That will make the inbound timeout to the default 60 seconds, and fix  the issue.

This can be done without any downtime. Please let me know if in agreement, I can create a RFC for you.
Regards,
Sreedar 
