G. UNIX SIGNALS

What is a Signal #1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, ..11, 15, ...?


Forms 4.5.10 and later (in other words all versions used by Oracle Applications) implement a signal handler to catch the UNIX signal that the operating system sends to terminate a process if it performs an invalid operation. This allows Forms to call code that reads the f60webmx executable and writes the stack to the Forms Server log file, and then close down cleanly.

UNIX Signals

All UNIX processes terminate with a signal, even if the user logged out normally. 
The signal can often provide useful information about why the process was terminated. For example, Signal 10 or Signal 11 indicates there was a program error, 
necessitating examination of the relevant stack trace to obtain further details. Other signals may identify more specific causes of failures.

When the Forms Server crashes or terminates prematurely, it is usually in response to a UNIX signal, sent either by the operating system, or possibly by another Forms Server process. If a Forms Server f60webmx process crashes, the signal is usually written to the end of the FRD log file, and can often give a clue as to the cause of the crash.
In contrast, if a user logs off cleanly, no signal will be seen at the end of the FRD log file, although truss output should show a final Signal 15.

The following is from signal.h - find the file you the UNIX system by going to /usr/include/ and then doing a find for signal.h: 
i.e. /usr/include/find . -name signal.h -print
Only signals 1-18 are listed, as these are the most common.
#define SIGHUP 1 /* hangup */
#define SIGINT 2 /* interrupt (rubout) */
#define SIGQUIT 3 /* quit (ASCII FS) */
#define SIGILL 4 /* illegal instruction (not reset when caught) */
#define SIGTRAP 5 /* trace trap (not reset when caught) */
#define SIGIOT 6 /* IOT instruction */
#define SIGABRT 6 /* used by abort, replace SIGIOT in the future */
#define SIGEMT 7 /* EMT instruction */
#define SIGFPE 8 /* floating point exception */
#define SIGKILL 9 /* kill (cannot be caught or ignored) */
#define SIGBUS 10 /* bus error */
#define SIGSEGV 11 /* segmentation violation */
#define SIGSYS 12 /* bad argument to system call */
#define SIGPIPE 13 /* write on a pipe with no one to read it */
#define SIGALRM 14 /* alarm clock */
#define SIGTERM 15 /* software termination signal from kill */
#define SIGUSR1 16 /* user defined signal 1 */
#define SIGUSR2 17 /* user defined signal 2 */
#define SIGCLD 18 /* child status change */

Below are some of the more common Unix Signals seen in Oracle Applications:
--> Signal 6 is often seen when the Forms process raises an assertion. The assertion error will normally be written to the console where the Forms listener was started, or to f60srvm.txt if UNIX standard output is redirected to this file. Generate an FRD log file with a reproducible test case

--> Signal 10 or 11, both of these signals generally occur in response to a program error, 
when the program tries to access an illegal memory address. 
A stack trace (core dump) should give more information about where it is crashing. 
If the f60webmx process is crashing, an FRD log file should be generated, and instructions to reproduce the problem supplied.

--> Signal 15, normally the process has shut itself down cleanly. It is obvious from the FRD log file that the user has logged out, by looking at the last action, and the last triggers that fire. The truss output also shows the Forms process terminating with Signal 15 when the user logs out cleanly.
Signal 15 at the end of an FRD when the user Hans�t logged out usually indicates that a problem was caused either by a client side java exception, or a middle tier process shut itself down cleanly when it could no longer communicate with the client. It has historically been difficult to predict whether this scenario will result in a timeout 14, or a Signal 15 following a client or network failure. However, in Forms 6i Patchset 5, the cause of process termination (timeout, network error etc.) is logged as activity in log file, making problem diagnosis much easier.

@ Internal reference: From Section 3.8 UNIX Signals in Chris White note: 
