In summary, customers using 11.5.10 should only be using LONG_RUNNING_JVM as CACHEMODE is deprecated (no longer used but still recognised as a valid parameter)

To the best of my understanding 
CACHEMODE=distributed is the same as LONG_RUNNING_JVM=true
CACHEMODE=local is the same as LONG_RUNNING_JVM=false

If LONG_RUNNING_JVM is not set, then it defaults to "false"

Historically, for customers with java cache issue we just got them to comment out LONG_RUNNING_JVM as not many applications actually used Java cache (Note 344132.1 for example). With 11.5.10, more and more applications now rely on this functionality so it is no longer recomended to disable Java Cache in this way as it could have serious implications on functionality

If disabling Java Cache solves a problem, then this implies there is a bug with Java Cache, so you will need to ensure that they have the latest patches and if problem persists then you need to raise a new bug. I hope that note 386568.1 provides enough information to help you with such an investigation, but if not then let me know and I will try to help and also improve the note for future reference
