Note 838808.1 Unable to Login to the B2B Console, Certificate Shows "This certificate has expired or is not yet valid"
Symptoms
When trying to access the B2B Console using Internet Explorer with SSL enabled, (i.e. https://host:port/b2b/ )  the following error occurs:

Certificate Information: This certificate has expired or is not yet valid 
 Valid from {date} to {date}

Cause
The wrong Certificate is being used for validation between B2B Apache Server (configured with SSL) and IE Browser.

Solution
B2B Application Server: 

1. Go to $B2B_ORACLE_HOME/Apache/Apache/conf/httpd.conf file and confirm if it has the line: 

$B2B_ORACLE_HOME/Apache/Apache/conf/ssl.conf
  This line defines the wallet files location.

2. Go to $ORACLE_HOME/Apache/Apache/conf/ssl.conf file and confirm the wallet files location under Server Wallet section, i.e: 

# Server Wallet: 
# The server wallet contains the servers certificate, private key 
# and trusted certificates. Set SSLWallet at the wallet directory 
# using the syntax: file:<path-to-wallet-directory> 
SSLWallet file:$B2B_ORACLE_HOME/Apache/Apache/conf/ssl.wlt/default 
3. Open the Oracle Wallet Manager and use the wallet created in the location defined in step 2. 
4. Check if the new certificate is in the wallet, if not, please import it. 
5. Remove old certificates.
6. Save the wallet in the location defined in step 2 (it will create the ewallet.p12 file). Please confirm that exist two files: 
- ewallet.p12 
- cwallet.sso 
7. Restart the B2B Server. 

Import Certificate into the Browser: 

1. In the PC where the Browser is installed leave a copy of ewallet.p12 file created in B2B Application Server section above. 
2. In the Internet Explorer browser Go to Tools -> Internet Options -> Content -> Certificates button. 
3. Click on the Import button. The Import Wizard will open, do a click on the Next button. 
4. Find the ewallet.p12 file and do a click on Next button.
5. Input the Wallet password in the Password Page, click on Next button. 
6. In the Certificate Store page, check the 'Place all certificates in the following store' radio button. 
7. Click on Browse, choose the Personal folder then click OK, and click on Next button. 
8. Click on Finish button. A new certificate will appear in the Personal Certificates store. 
9. Find old certificates and remove them. 
10. Restart Internet Explorer. 
11. Open the B2B Console.

References
<<NOTE:356712.1>> - How to Obtain a User Certificate With Oracle Wallet Manager and Install it into Internet Explorer For Use With SSO Digital Certificate Sign-On
