How to Control the Set of Top SQLs Captured During AWR Snapshot Generation (Doc ID 554831.1)


The table WRH$_ACTIVE_SESSION_HISTORY is growing to a large size.  It is suspected that it may be an issue with purging (similar to the problem described in Note 387914.1). However, it appears purging works correctly, and the output from the following query shows default values for snap_interval (1 hour) and retention period (7 days) which is correct: 

set linesize 200
col snap_interval format a30
col retention format a20
col most_recent_purge_time format a30
select snap_interval, retention, most_recent_purge_time from sys.wrm$_wr_control;

The problem can be because of high value for TOPNSQL. 
If it was never modified, the following querys output is 'DEFAULT':
 SQL> select TOPNSQL  from DBA_HIST_WR_CONTROL;
 and the following query would give the actual (likely very big) number:
 SQL> select TOPNSQL from sys.wrm$_wr_control;
The TOPNSQL setting affects the number of Top SQL to flush for each SQL criteria (Elapsed Time, CPU Time, Parse Calls, Shareable Memory, and Version Count). The value for this setting will not be affected by the statistics/flush level and will override the system default behavior for the AWR SQL collection. It is possible to set the value for this setting to a very high number to capture the complete set of SQL in the cursor cache, although by doing so may lead to possible space and performance issues since there will be more data to collect and store.
To adjust the settings, use the MODIFY_SNAPSHOT_SETTINGS procedure of  DBMS_WORKLOAD_REPOSITORY package:

SQL> exec DBMS_WORKLOAD_REPOSITORY.MODIFY_SNAPSHOT_SETTINGS(topnsql => 100);
For majority of databases even value of 30 is sufficient, but this can affect precision of the Oracle diagnostic tools. 
