With regard to debugging AQ PL/SQL notification the mechanism works in the following way

1. PL/SQL callback procedure is registered
2. Publisher enqueues message onto a queue
3. Emon is posted by the enqueue session
4. Up to and including 11.1 the notification is re-enqueued into a persistent queue AQ_SRVNTFN_TABLE_Q
5 A register_driver job is created for each message
Prior to 11.1 this is a dbms_job and 11.1 onwards it is a dbms_scheduler
job for which the action is the same as before namely register_driver
6 The job queue process dequeues the notification and executes the specified callback.

The debug steps are fairly limited and they are

1. Check that the PL/SQL procedures are registered in sys.reg$
2. Check for messages in AQ_SRVNTFN_TABLE_Q via

connect / as sysdba

select count(*), msg_state, queue from AQ$AQ_SRVNTFN_TABLE group by msg_state, queue;

3. Identify the job_queue_process dequeueing the messages

select p.spid, p.program from v$process p, dba_jobs_running jr, v$session s, dba_jobs j where s.sid=jr.sid and s.paddr=p.addr and jr.job=j.job and j.what like '%register_driver%';

Note that when working normally register driver jobs will have a very short lifetime as they are processing just one message.

4. Check for job_queue_process trace files in the bdump destination

5. If there are no job_queue_process trace files containing an error for each process id (spid) identified by step 3 attach to it via oradebug and generate sql trace

oradebug setospid
oradebug unlimit
oradebug Event 10046 trace name context forever, level 12
--Trace the process for 15 minutes
oradebug Event 10046 trace name context off

Repeat for each process. As per 3 you would only be able to do this if the register driver jobs are stuck.

6 In the situation that the register_driver() jobs run forever and do not terminate or process user-enqueued messages run the query below
to identify which notification messages exist in the AQ_SRVNTFN_TABLE_Q and no longer exist in the Application Queue.

connect / as sysdba

select msgid notify_msgid, to_char(n.enq_time,'DD-MON-YYYY hh24:mi:ss'), n.user_data.msg_id app_msgid, 
n.user_data.queue_name qname, nvl(utl_raw.cast_to_varchar2(n.user_data.payload),'null') payload 
from sys.aq_srvntfn_table n 
where n.user_data.msg_id in (select n.user_data.msg_id msgid from sys.aq_srvntfn_table n minus select msgid from 'APP_SCHEMANAME.APP_QUEUE_TABLENAME') 
and n.user_data.queue_name = 'APP_SCHEMANAME.APP_QUEUENAME';



where 'APP_SCHEMANAME.APP_QUEUE_TABLENAME` and 'APP_SCHEMANAME.APP_QUEUENAME? are replaced with appropriate values for the user created queue.

