Required background processes.
http://oracledba.ezpowell.com/oracle/instanceArchitectureInternalInstanceProcesses.html


SMON - the server monitor process recovers temporary segment space when no longer required and colesces contiguous areas of free space in database tablespaces. 
PMON - the process monitor cleans up failed transactions. 
DBWR - the database dirty write buffer process writes modified/changed (dirty) blocks from the database buffer cache to disk files. 
In general the primary purpose of the DBWR is the management of the database buffer cache such that the server processes can always find free buffers. 
On commit the DBWR clears the rollback segments and writes database buffer cache blocks to disk. 
On rollback the DBWR removes changes to the database cache and clears the rollback segments. 

LGWR - the log writer process writes out the redo buffer to the redo logs on a commit statement. 

CKPT - checkpoint process. Required in Oracle8. 


Optional processes.


ARCH - the archiver process copies filled redo logs to the archive logs. 
RECO - required on distributed databases. 
SNPn - snapshot/job queue process. 
LCKn - n is 0 to 9, one per parallel instance required. 
Dnnn - dispatcher process for multi-threaded server (MTS). In an MTS environment client user processes are connected to the database via a dispathcer process. The dispatcher will support multiple concurrent client connections. The dispatcher process manages a section of memory shared by all client connections as a way of handling database access. Note that Net8 in Oracle8 (not SQL*Net) is required to support connections to the database utilising MTS. 
Snnn - server process for MTS. 
QMNn - queue manager process is used with Oracle advanced queuing. 
Pnnn - parallel query slave process for parallel query option (PQO). 


