How to check for it (Rediscovery):

When you check for AWR or EM, you will find one of the following SQLs appear with very high number of executions:

SQL #1:
SELECT R.Conc_Login_Id, R.Request_Id, R.Phase_Code, R.Status_Code, P.Application_ID, P.Concurrent_Program_ID, P.Concurrent_Program_Name, R.Enable_Trace, R.Restart, DECODE(R.Increment_Dates, 'Y', 'Y', 'N'), R.NLS_Compliant, R.OUTPUT_FILE_TYPE, E.Executable_Name, E.Execution_File_Name, A2.Basepath, DECODE(R.Stale, 'Y', 'C', P.Execution_Method_Code),
...
....
FOR UPDATE OF R.status_code NoWait

SQL #2:
Select R.Rowid From Fnd_Concurrent_Requests R Where R.Hold_Flag = 'N' And R.Status_Code = 'I' And R.Requested_Start_Date <= Sysdate And ((R.OPS_INSTANCE is NULL) OR (R.OPS_INSTANCE = -1) OR (R.OPS_INSTANCE = FND_CONC_GLOBAL.OPS_INST_NUM)) AND EXISTS....
..
..
ORDER BY NVL(R.priority, 999999999), R.Priority_Request_ID, R.Request_ID

The mere fact that it appears in AWR or EM itself means it has to be addressed. The seen effects (via EM and AWR) are just the high number of executions - and you will also see the parse rate go up (like hard parse per sec)
The unseen effects are:
1. In a RAC:
  - you will see unexplained "gcs*" events. The events include but not limited to: "gcs buffer busy", "gcs sync"
  - in more severe cases you will see standard programs wait on concurrency.
  - Entire instance will go slow, not just a single node.
2. In a non-RAC:
  - most commonly you will see even normally efficient standard Apps PLSQLs waiting on concurrency
  - commonly, high hard parse count.
  - for <= 9i: "shared pool" and "library cache" events
  - for => 10g: unexplained "*mutex*" events for normally quick PLSQL.

Solution:
The solution is twofold:
1. if you find SQL #1 from above alone:
   Check for sleep time and cache sizes and adjust as appropriate.
   use SQL:
   --Sleep secs etc 

        SELECT fcqt.CONCURRENT_QUEUE_NAME Q_NM,
          USER_CONCURRENT_QUEUE_NAME U_Q_NM,
          ENABLED_FLAG Ena,
          cache_size CAC,
          TARGET_PROCESSES PROC,
          sleep_seconds SLP,
          (select user_name from applsys.fnd_user where fcqt.Last_updated_BY=user_id) Update_by,
          fcqt.Last_UPDATE_DATE LAST_UPD
        FROM applsys.fnd_concurrent_queues fcq,
          applsys.fnd_concurrent_queues_tl fcqt
        WHERE fcq.CONCURRENT_QUEUE_ID=fcqt.CONCURRENT_QUEUE_ID
        AND (sleep_seconds            < 60  OR cache_size < 2*target_processes)
        and target_processes > 1
         and (fcqt.concurrent_queue_name not in ('PODAMGR','FNDICM','FNDCRM'))
        and enabled_flag='Y'
        and fcqt.language='US'
          ;
        Go through the output, make sure that there are no critical managers like PO document approval manager that the customer might need specifically low sleep seconds.
        I have in the past used sleep seconds=60 and cache=2x the # of processes.
        But it is acceptable to have lesser sleep seconds upto 30 seconds as long as cache size is set properly (but do not set so low sleep_seconds for all managers, only select few)

    This issue is documented in Metalink note:
    Concurrent Processing - One Concurrent Manager SQL Statement Shows Excessive Executions (Doc ID 1066332.1)

2. If you see SQL #2 only or both SQLs from above:
   implement solution above for SQL #1 and check for below bug and apply patch.
    Release 11i customer should apply patch 9109247 SCHEDULED REQUESTS STILL RUN FOR END_DATED USERS 100% CPU . Patch 9109247 upgrades version of afperq.lc to 115.44 .
